{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"86fa059e-bba8-4e11-b9cc-12d730eb5fa0","content":"The repository doesn't contain documentation on this topic, so here's the general guidance:\n\n## Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`\n\nNativeAOT apps don't bundle `createdump`. On macOS, use the **OS-native mechanisms**:\n\n1. **Enable core dumps** — macOS disables them by default:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n\n2. **Run your app** — when it crashes, macOS writes a core file to `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n3. **Check `/cores/`** for the dump:\n   ```bash\n   ls -la /cores/\n   ```\n\n4. **If `/cores/` is empty**, macOS may have generated a `.crash` log instead. Find it at:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   or system-wide:\n   ```\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\n5. **Analyze the core dump** with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n6. **If SIP blocks core dumps**, you may need to temporarily adjust settings or use `lldb` to attach directly:\n   ```bash\n   lldb /path/to/your/app\n   run\n   # after crash, use `bt` for backtrace\n   ```\n\n**Key notes:**\n- The `/cores/` directory must exist and be writable.\n- On Apple Silicon, make sure you're not hitting `kern.coredump=0` — check with `sysctl kern.coredump` and set to `1` if needed.\n- `.crash` reports in `DiagnosticReports` contain symbolicated stack traces and are often sufficient for initial triage.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0c53c0b6-341f-47de-ae6e-a0cf8ee6f017","outputTokens":428,"requestId":"418C:1EA9D4:6466D0F:6DA0F50:69F163D2"},"id":"d6a0a6f8-302e-42bc-ade6-ed1a7d0109f7","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:50:21.858Z","parentId":"524629a1-92f6-43f8-9777-6fd88a33f681"}
